            "title": "Mine water management: how miners can benefit",
            "abstract": "The mining industry uses 2%-3% of Australia\u2019s water, but the cost of supply is ten times higher than for agricultural uses. Mining activities produce various volumes of water which must be managed at surface, and it is suggested that much can be learnt from the coal seam industry in Queensland and New South Wales where studies undertaken to support major approvals are directly relevant to water management at mine sites in these states. Coal seam gas water in Queensland was historically stored in large evaporation ponds but this option is no longer viable due to environmental concerns and the increase in groundwater extraction volumes, and innovative water management techniques are now required for new water regulations. The strategies are site specific and options can include on-site uses, water treatment, water sharing, managed aquifer recharge, surface infiltration and virtual recharge. The use of management and disposal options can be planned and optimised to respond to changes in water production, operational requirements and climatic conditions through tools such as dynamic site-wide water balance models",
